      <div class="realpost"><div>
        <blockquote class="thequote">Since power over human beings is shown in making them do what they would rather not do, the man who is actuated by love of power is more apt to inflict pain than to permit pleasure. If you ask your boss for leave of absence from the office on some legitimate occasion, his love of power will derive more satisfaction from a refusal than from a consent. If you require a building permit, the petty official concerned will obviously get more pleasure from saying «No» than from saying «Yes». It is this sort of thing which makes the love of power such a dangerous motive.</blockquote>
        &mdash;<a href="http://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/literature/laureates/1950/russell-lecture.html">Bertrand Russell</a>
